Patterns in plant species diversity along the altitudinal gradient in Dhauladhar mountain range of the North-West Himalaya in Indiaâ˜†

Highlights

  • â€¢

    Dhauladhar mountain range of the North-West Himalaya supports diverse forest communities along the altitudinal gradient, of which temperate forest endows with maximum forest communities.

  • â€¢

    There is a hump-shaped curve in the species diversity of woody plant species along an altitudinal gradient.

  • â€¢

    Species diversity of herbaceous species increases with elevations from sub-tropical to sub-alpine forests.

  • â€¢

Abstract

The objective of the present study was to understand the patterns in plant species diversity along the altitudinal gradient in Dhauladhar mountain range of the Indian Himalayas. Nested plot method was employed for sampling trees, shrubs and herbs along the elevations from sub-tropical forests to sub-alpine forests, and Shannon-Weiner diversity index was used for calculation of plant species diversity. A total of 10 forest communities were identified, of which the highest number of forest communities and woody species diversity were found in the temperate forests. Though, there are multiple ecological factors and their combinations which determine the distribution and diversity of plant species in an ecosystem, the present study reveals that elevation is one of the major abiotic factors in the Himalayan mountains, which determines the establishment and distribution of various forest communities and species diversity. Along an altitudinal gradient there was a hump-shaped curve in the species diversity of woody plant species whereas the species diversity of herbaceous species increased with elevations from sub-tropical to sub-alpine forests. This fact needs to be employed while making policies and planning for the sustainability of forests along the altitudinal gradients in the mountains.

1. Introduction

Mountains across the world are the most remarkable land forms, which sustain unique biodiversity with prominent vegetation zones along altitudinal gradient (Khan et al., 2012; Antonelli et al., 2018). The Himalayan mountain ecosystem, despite the youngest mountain of the world, is well-known for its rich and exceptional floral and faunal diversity (Mani, 1978; Rawal and Dhar, 1997; Singh et al., 1996). Varieties of ecosystem services are provided by Himalayan mountain ecosystem to a large population in Asia therefore it is imperative to maintain this unique ecosystem (Kala, 2014, 2015a; Badola et al., 2015, Bhatt, Negi and Rawal, 2020. Even the agriculture system in the Himalayas has also developed close linkages with the surrounding forests, which help to protect the soil fertility, biodiversity, and ecosystem stability (Bawa et al., 2007; Singh et al., 2016).

The forest management in India primarily focuses on the structural diversity of various woody plant species (Verma, 2008; Kala, 2015b). There are studies, which report that woody plant species diversity can be used to predict the diversity patterns of all plant species in forest ecosystems (Qian and Kissling, 2010; Giorgini et al., 2015). Since woody species help to sustain habitats and provide resources to all other associated species their diversity one way or another indicates biodiversity of the concerned forest types (Bhat et al., 2020). Likewise, understanding the forest communities discloses the fact that how different species coexist in a particular ecosystem and environmental gradient. There are multiple factors and their combinations which determine the distribution and diversity of species in an ecosystem. Such complexities aggravate in the mountain ecosystem due to heterogeneity of the landforms and so that the environmental heterogeneity (Gaston, 2000; Clarke and Gaston, 2006), and intensity of disturbances, both of natural and anthropogenic origin (Wade et al., 2003; Kala, 2015b).

In Himalayas, apart from aspect and degree of slope, altitude is also known to play an important role in formation of various forest communities and diversity of woody species in such communities (Majila and Kala, 2010; Pant and Samant, 2012). The heterogeneity in slope-aspect and elevation within a landform show a significant relationship with habitat heterogeneity (Aguilar-Santelises and del Castillo, 2013). In general, a rise of 270 m in the mountains correspond to a fall of 10 Â°C in mean temperature upto 1500 m, and above this altitude temperature fall is more rapid (Mani, 1974). Therefore, change in mean temperature along the elevations is one of the prime factors, which leads to establish the forest communities and species diversity.

The assessment of species diversity encompasses the variety and variability of life forms therefore the species diversity indices, which include both the variables, help to understand the health of the ecosystem and also the various anthropogenic and natural disturbances (Kala, 1998; Thapa and Chapman, 2010; Fedor and ZvarÃ­kovÃ¡, 2019). Altitude being one of the prime factors in the Himalayas influencing various life forms, it has to be studied not only with respect to the availability and adaptability of plant species but also for understanding the structure of forest communities. Regular monitoring, analysis and evaluation of various components of the Himalayan ecosystem, including forest communities and species diversity, may help to formulate proper planning and policy interventions with respect to the long-term sustainability of the Himalayas and so that the survival of human beings.

Studies have been conducted on the species diversity in various parts of the North West Himalaya (Kala 2004; Sharma et al., 2010; Gairola et al., 2011; Verma and Kapoor 2011; Pant and Samant 2012; Pokhriyal et al., 2012; Dar and Sundarapandian 2016; Singh et al., 2016) however most of the studies are localized in nature and cover limited altitudinal range. The present study, therefore, attempts to cover the larger altitudinal range for understanding the patterns in species diversity along the elevations from sub-tropical to sub-alpine forests.

2. Methods

2.1. Study area

The present study was carried out in Kangra district of Himachal Pradesh in India. Kangra district is located in Dhauladhar mountain range of the Indian Himalayas between 31Â°2 and 32Â°5 N and 75Â°â€“77,045 E (Fig. 1). It spans over 5729 sq. km encompassing wide range of elevation from 427 to 6401 m above mean sea level. This wide altitudinal range helps to sustain the rich biodiversity across the forest types, including sub-tropical, moist temperate (both broadleaf and coniferous) and sub-alpine forests (Sharma and Kala, 2022). As per the Forest Survey of India, the recorded forest cover in the district is 2354 sq. km, which spans over 41% of the district geographical area. Most of the forests cover (1288.65 sq. km) falls under moderately dense forest cover category, followed by open forest (766.78 sq. km) and very dense forests (298.76 sq. km; FSI, 2019).

The study area endows with rich faunal and avifaunal diversity, including musk deer, leopard, Himalayan tahr, Himalayan black bear, goral, blue sheep, western tragopan, Himalayan monal, snow partridge, koklass and white crested kalij (Sharma, 2017). The maximum mean temperature in the study area varies from 18.32 Â°C to 30.8 Â°C and the minimum mean temperature ranges from 1.23 Â°C to 29.2 Â°C. The annual rainfall ranges from 147.37 to 228.43 mm (Sharma, 2017). The soils in district are shallow black, brown and alluvial. The major portion of the district falls within the drainage basin of Beas where soils are alluvial silty loam with high fertility status (Department of Agriculture, 2009). The human population in Kangra district is 1507,223, which is highest among all districts of Himachal Pradesh. Animal husbandry, agriculture, horticulture and collection of non-timber forest produce are the major occupations of the local people.

2.2. Forest stratification and sampling

To study the patterns in species diversity along the altitudinal gradient, the study area was divided into three zones based on the altitude and forest types, such as, subtropical forests (1000â€“1500 m), temperate forests (1501â€“3000 m) and subalpine forests (>3000 m) following Champion and Seth (1968). Nested plot method was employed for sampling trees, shrubs and herbs following Misra (1968). The quadrats of 10 Ã— 10 m for trees, 5 Ã— 5 m for shrubs and 1 Ã— 1 m for herbs were laid down in each zone. A total of 1106 sampling plots were laid along the altitudinal gradients. Plant species with their individuals were enumerated in each quadrat. The communities were identified based on the dominance of woody species in particular localities.

2.3. Quantitative analysis

The Shannon-Weiner diversity index (Shannon and Weaver, 1949) has been used by most of the researchers in the past for measuring plant species diversity in the North-West Himalayas. The Shannon-Weiner diversity index, therefore, was used for calculation of plant species diversity as per the following formula:H'=âˆ’âˆ‘pilogpi

Since there are number of studies available on the plant species diversity in the North-West Himalayas and most of them have used the Shannon-Weiner diversity index, the use and application of the same index further helps in drawing comparison in plant species diversity of the present study area with other similar localities in the North-West Himalayas.

3. Results

A total of 184 plant species were sampled during the present investigations in the study area. These species were distributed over 165 genera and 78 families, of which 154 genera representing 71 families belonged to Angiosperm, 7 genera representing 3 families belonged to Gymnosperms and 4 genera with 4 families belonged to Pteridophytes. Of the total species, 41 were tree species, 29 shrub species, 91 herbaceous species, 7 ferns and rest of the 16 species were comprised of climbers, epiphytes, and grasses (Table 1). The highest number of plant species (116 species including 25 tree species, 13 shrub species and 78 herbaceous species) was recorded in the temperate forests, followed by sub-tropical forests (68 species including 21 tree species, 12 shrub species and 35 herbaceous species) and sub-alpine forests (51 species including 8 tree species, 7 shrub species and 36 herbaceous species). The temperate forests were the center of woody plant species richness and species diversity as the highest percentage of woody plant species (both trees and shrubs) was found in the temperate forests (60% trees and 45% shrubs), followed by sub-tropical (50% trees and 41% shrubs) and sub-alpine forests (19% trees and 24% shrubs).

Along the altitudinal gradient in the study area a total of 10 forest community types were identified, of which the highest number of forest community was found in the temperate forests. Of the 6 forest community types in the temperate forests, four of them were dominated by Quercus spp. (either by Quercus leucotrichophora or by Quercus semecarpifolia). Cedrus deodara, Rhododendron arboreum, and Acer sp. were the major associate tree species of Quercus leucotrichophora community whereas Abies pindrow was the major associate tree species in Quercus semecarpifolia community.

The species diversity of woody plant species (tree and shrub) was higher in the temperate forests in comparison to sub-tropical and sub-alpine forests. Three forest communities such as Pinus roxburghii, Pinus wallichiana and Quercus semecarpifolia were predominated by single tree species hence they mainly formed pure stands. Pinus roxburghii community was found in the sub-tropical forest whereas the rest two single tree dominated communities namely Pinus wallichiana and Quercus semecarpifolia were located in the temperate forests (Photographs 1â€“4).

Among all the forest communities along the altitudinal gradient, the tree species diversity was highest in the Picea smithiana - Cedrus deodara - Abies pindrow - Pinus wallichiana community (Hâ€™=2.84), followed by Quercus leucotrichophora - Acer sp. - Taxus wallichiana - Betula utilis community (Hâ€™=2.78), and Quercus semecarpifolia community (Hâ€™=2.69). Among the pure tree stands community Quercus semecarpifolia community was richest in species diversity, followed by Pinus wallichiana community (Table 2). The lowest tree species diversity was found in the Pinus roxburghii community in the sub-tropical forests (Hâ€™=2.01) and Betula utilis - Picea smithiana - Rhododendron campanulatum community in the sub-alpine forests (Hâ€™=2.04).

The species diversity of shrub species also varied along the altitudinal gradient across the forest communities (Hâ€™=2.00â€“2.46). Likewise, the tree species diversity, the highest shrub diversity (Hâ€™=2.46) was found in Picea smithiana - Cedrus deodara - Abies pindrow - Pinus wallichiana community, followed by Quercus semecarpifolia community and Quercus semecarpifolia - Abies pindrow community (Hâ€™=2.31). The species diversity of herbaceous species was lowest in Pinus roxburghii (Hâ€™=2.09) and Pinus wallichiana (Hâ€™=2.01) forest communities. The highest species diversity of herbs was estimated for Betula utilis - Picea smithiana - Rhododendron campanulatum forest community in the sub-alpine forests (Hâ€™=3.01).

4. Discussion

The present study reveals that the elevation is one of the major factors in the Himalayan mountains, which determines the establishment and existence of various forest communities and species diversity. Similar observations are made for the mountainous region, elsewhere, that the elevation as a regional environmental factor best predicts the diversity and distribution of woody species (Bacaro et al., 2008). Along an altitudinal gradient there was a hump-shaped curve in the species diversity of woody plant species whereas the species diversity of herbaceous species increased with elevations from sub-tropical to sub-alpine forests in the present study area.

Studies conducted elsewhere in various parts of the North-West Himalaya in India indicate wide range in tree species diversity (Hâ€™=0.45â€“3.37) across various localities within temperate forests. The lowest tree species diversity (Hâ€™=0.45) is reported from Khirsu region of Pauri Garhwal district of Uttarakhand state (Sharma et al., 2010), whereas the highest tree species diversity (Hâ€™=3.37) is reported from the Kedarnath Wildlife Sanctuary in Chamoli district of Uttarakhand (Bhat et al., 2020). In sub-alpine forests, the tree species diversity varies from Hâ€™=0.17 in Anantnag district of Jammu and Kashmir (Dar and Sundarapandian, 2016) to Hâ€™=2.29 in Kedarnath Wildlife Sanctuary (Bhat et al., 2020). Generally, the human access and anthropogenic disturbances remain marginal in the sub-alpine forests but the environmental stresses stay high, which subsequently result in the low species diversity of woody plant species. Though the range of species diversity varies in other parts of the North-West Himalaya, the general pattern in species diversity remains almost similar along the elevations (Table 3).

There are two prominent patterns in tree species diversity across various forests types along the elevations in the Himalayas. Either there is a hump-shaped curve in the species diversity or there is a continuous decline in tree species diversity along the altitudinal gradients. Within temperate forests, continuous decline is reported in the tree species diversity along the elevation from 2250 m to 2800 m (Sharma et al., 2009). The Forest Survey of India's (2019) study on the tree species diversity of Himachal Pradesh reports highest tree species diversity to the Himalayan moist temperate forests (Hâ€™=2.95), followed by subtropical pine forests (Hâ€™=2.63), Himalayan dry temperate forests (Hâ€™=2.03), and sub-alpine forests (Hâ€™=1.64; FSI, 2019). Further, the shrub species diversity is also reported highest in the Himalayan moist temperate forests (Hâ€™=3.25), followed by Himalayan dry temperate forests (Hâ€™=2.56), subtropical pine forests (Hâ€™=2.17), and lowest in the sub-alpine forests (Hâ€™=1.83; FSI, 2019).

Generally, the temperate forests remain the center of high tree species diversity along the elevations from sub-tropical to sub-alpine forests however there are possibilities of locality-specific variations in species diversity due to microclimatic conditions, landforms, soil properties and level of anthropogenic disturbances (Shrestha et al., 1999; Dar and Sundarapandian, 2016; Bhatt et al., 2020). A study conducted in Phakot watershed of Tehri Garhwal of Uttarakhand (Pokhriyal et al., 2012) reports higher tree species diversity in sub-tropical forests (Hâ€™=2.41â€“2.44) than the temperate forests (Hâ€™=1.16â€“1.44). Relatively low species diversity in sub-tropical forests in the present study area may be due to number of causes including heavy anthropogenic pressures and invasion of Lantana camera (Sharma and Kala, 2018). The predominance of Pinus roxburghii is also considered the cause of low species diversity in the sub-tropical forests (Sharma et al., 2010).

The present study ascertains the fact that the tree species diversity remains higher in the temperate forests dominated by conifers than the broadleaf forests in the sub-tropical and sub-alpine forests. Various anthropogenic pressures may alter the composition and species diversity of forests along the altitudes. This fact is expected to be employed while making policies and planning for the sustainability of forests along the altitudinal gradients in the mountains so that the ecosystem services provided by these unique forests may be continued for posterity. There is a need for continuous assessment and monitoring of forests in the Himalayas for ascertaining the changes in the species diversity over the years, which may help to further guide the management interventions.

  • Elevational pattern, structure, and regeneration status of woody taxa along a semi-disturbed timberline ecotone in northwestern Himalayas

    2022, Acta Ecologica Sinica

    The composition, structure, and patterns of vegetation undergo a noticeable shift along the elevational gradient, and this is regulated by various abiotic variables, primarily the elevation and edaphic characteristics. The present study investigated the change in community characteristics of woody vegetation along a vertical gradient from 2800 m till 4000 m in parts of upper Bani Wildlife Sanctuary in Jammu and Kashmir. In all, 40 woody species were recorded including 11 trees and 29 shrubs with a distinctive hump shaped pattern that becomes steeper with the rising elevation. Sm. and D.Don. exhibited a wide elevational range (3000â€“3500 m asl), eventually forming the climatic climax along southern and northern aspects. The diversity and phytosociological attributes peaked at intermediate elevation with =1.74 recorded for trees and =2.48 observed for shrubs. The average density and basal cover for trees and shrubs ranged between 75.50 Nha & 20.09 mha and 69.31 Nha & 4.50 mha, respectively. The species turnover rate was recorded high in case of trees (0.11â€“0.77) and low for shrubs (0.17â€“0.29). A modest density of 114 seedlings ha and 249 saplings ha was recorded across the forest types. The low seedling (0.22) and sapling (0.48) per tree ratio indicated a low regeneration performance anticipating a very slow upslope movement of the tree line. This may result in population decline of a few select species in future, necessitating effective monitoring and management intervention for which these findings will be helpful.
